When importing, we will update the new created backup with
old volume id. In fact, we need to keep the volume_id attribute
set empty (00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000) in order to

Closes-Bug: #1780386

commit_message:
Don't update volume_id in backup manager when import backup

When importing, we will update the new created backup with
old volume id. In fact, we need to keep the volume_id attribute
set empty (00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000000) in order to
avoid confusing.

Change-Id: I30f8188796bc0e0d744109c116c71ce1477fc14f
Closes-Bug: #1780386

commit_message:
Add missing image metadata when creating volume from backup

Add the missing bootable flag and image metadata when creating
volume from the backup that was created from an image volume
previously.

Change-Id: Ibd454f83c1db1c7b401866e70f21035fb290cd2d
Closes-Bug: #1769634

commit_message:
Option needed to create volume in erasure coded ceph pool

Erasure coded pools for rbd have been supported since the ceph
luminous release. To use this feature the erasure coded pool where
the data will be held needs to be specified during volume creation.
The rbd_pool option still needs to point to a replicated pool where
a small amount of metadata will be stored in OMAP. Currently the
driver implicitly uses the default value of None.

Change-Id: I3128d3f82cdc09531a33d3b3dd27b624b907236e
Closes-Bug: 1779691

commit_message:
Group model: ensure 'volume_types' are mapped to VolumeTypes

If 'volume_types' for expected_attrs is being used, volume_types
returned is actually mapped to the GroupVolumeTypeMapping
model rather than the VolumeTypes model. This corresponds
to the following staticmethod Group._from_db_object in cinder/objects/group.py:

  if 'volume_types' in expected_attrs:
      volume_types = base.obj_make_list(
          context, objects.VolumeTypeList(context),
          objects.VolumeType,
          db_group['volume_types'])

This change ensures that the 'volume_types' member of Group object is
correctly mapped to VolumeTypes. We implemented it using primaryjoin
and secondaryjoin arguments of sqlalchemy.orm.relationship to define
a column in Group model.

Closes-Bug: #1756867

Change-Id: I51d98b4c479a995f9758b10389864d258f95ef1f

I think it may be more 'accurate' when there's only one scheduler(and if operation failed at backend, the scheduler will be notified and do some reversion). In most case, multiple schedulers co-exist, that means api requests will be sent to a random scheduler, then if we get pool stats from a scheduler's internal data, we could get inconsistent results(say, there are two scheduler A and B, and the backup currently has 100GB available. hmm, only one scheduler is allowed currently, and regarding that we may face many issues (other than this one) if we just turn multi-schedulers on."}, {'account_id': 13157, 'date': '2018-02-12 01:10:51.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

As cinder-volume broadcasts usage stats periodically, this should not be a serious problem most of the time, i.e. scheduler stats will be corrected by the next broadcasted 'update_service_capabilitier'."}, {'account_id': 24815, 'date': '2018-02-25 15:02:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Get pools API doesn't reflect capacity change

Cinder will update pool's capacity attributes
when creating new resource, but the get-pools API
doesn't reflect these changes. This patch try to
fix this by updating capabilities from attributes.

Change-Id: Idb1b85575fc2c8be7e6d0707cc5f2a931a1d0fbd
Closes-Bug: #1748696

commit_message:
Support EventAlarming description in TOSCA

This patch supports new tosca policy
"tosca.policies.tacker.EventAlarming"

* Add this new policy section to definition yaml
* Support read and translate this new policy section
* Support multiple type polices, such as using
  "tosca.policies.tacker.EventAlarming" and
  "tosca.policies.tacker.Alarming" in 1 VNF.

Note:
This feature is supposed to be used from the VNF creation
using the API '/vnfs', which is a legacy features based on NFV-IFA.
Support for API '/vnflcm' based on the latest NFV-SOL is T.B.D.

Implements: bp/add-event-alarm-policy
Change-Id: Ifcc40adfa4f0dd7cecb4d4ab3cb79e9032a934f3

commit_message:
Add image id compare

If the image has been updated on disk, the podman_container isn't
rebuild to use the new container.  This change adds an image id check to
the image check to see if the image name and tag are the same but the id
of the image has changed. It should be noted that the podman_container
does not fetch the updated image as it simply checks if it exists. A
user needs to use podman_image with force: True prior to running
podman_container to hit this condition.

Change-Id: Icb718d1c1ea9b829a532c37844ffb3c8b5db5dbe
Related-Bug: #1895974

commit_message:
Fix type of public_net_allocation_pools

https://review.opendev.org/#/c/733598/ added support
of allocation_pools, but set type of public_net_allocation_pools
to comma_delimited_list which causes below issue because for
comma_delimited_list, list items are converted to string:-

Property error: : resources.public_subnet.properties.allocation_pools[0]:
"{'end': '10.0.0.199', 'start': '10.0.0.128'}" is not a map

We need to use type: json to get it work, this patch fixes it.

Related-Bug: #1874418
Change-Id: Iaebb297e5018ce8db6dd1f67a308e7707117fe03

commit_message:
Documentation for Share Migration Ocata Improvements.

Implemented several improvements to share migration in documentation
according to https://review.opendev.org/#/c/406305/

Summary of changes:

 - Add driver-assisted mandatory parameters.
 - Removed previous API documentation because support for them isn't
   there anymore after the backwards incompatible changes were
   made via https://review.opendev.org/#/c/406305/.
 - Add force-host-assisted migration.

Change-Id: I6d446b4037a3a9991e375f0a8bfb1f6edce09c1f
Closes-Bug: #1658230

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-06-09 18:33:23.000000000', 'message': 'Update lower-constraints versions

This updates lower constraints to versions that will work with py38 so
that when we move to running on focal nodes, which has py38 as its
default py3 runtime, the lower-constraints job will continue to pass.

It also cleans out some secondary requirements that are no longer needed
due to our direct dependencies being updated.

Linters are removed that are kept in the global requirements blacklist
as those are not version tracked and are not relevant for our
lower-constraints unit test runs.

Change-Id: Id7c84958bee19d24e2088fb9cce8522fdafd1c15
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>
'}]
commit_message:
Update lower-constraints versions

This updates lower constraints to versions that will work with py38 so
that when we move to running on focal nodes, which has py38 as its
default py3 runtime, the lower-constraints job will continue to pass.

It also cleans out some secondary requirements that are no longer needed
due to our direct dependencies being updated.

Linters are removed that are kept in the global requirements blacklist
as those are not version tracked and are not relevant for our
lower-constraints unit test runs.

Change-Id: Id7c84958bee19d24e2088fb9cce8522fdafd1c15
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Update lower-constraints versions

This updates lower constraints to versions that will work with py38 so
that when we move to running on focal nodes, which has py38 as its
default py3 runtime, the lower-constraints job will continue to pass.

It also cleans out some secondary requirements that are no longer needed
due to our direct dependencies being updated.

Linters are removed that are kept in the global requirements blacklist
as those are not version tracked and are not relevant for our
lower-constraints unit test runs.

Change-Id: I6add044c00cb39d23d72df575a96e5367f67d26d
Signed-off-by: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/victoria

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/victoria branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I6ad6fd1c3d0b3c9172cb7953cc50f8ad8f4bf9de

commit_message:
Fix CA file for API client

If a custom CA file is configured via OPENSTACK_SSL_CACERT, currently
communication with Keystone will fail, since the session is not created
using this CA file.

This change fixes the issue by passing the path to the CA file to the
keystoneauth session constructor.

Change-Id: Iad1bdea97ed649cc3c8f042dc5dd147b989dfd0e
Closes-Bug: #1873736

commit_message:
Remove Barbican installation from gates

Apparently Barbican is Octavia requirements only if we're doing TLS
offload on the LB. As we're just doing HTTPS passthrough it shouldn't be
required for our use case and should be safe to remove.

Change-Id: Ic2f6297691cd6bfe9def6d5d6ba0dea24579bfcc

commit_message:
Make the MTU attribute not nullable

This patch sets the MTU attribute to non-nullable, the code
that get the MTU and update the network in some methods can
be removed. If the MTU is empty before the pike version, it
is set to the default value of 1500.

Change-Id: Id4d738dde7fa4b7caccabad0aac542b82b4d7af1
Closes-Bug: #1842261

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for zaqar

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for zaqar.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: Iced4332675752413526f47aa4dabc487d6c32b1b
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

[{'created': '2020-09-18 04:08:53.000000000', 'message': "Fix redfish BIOS to use @Redfish.SettingsApplyTime

This change fixes the 'redfish' BIOS interface implementation's
apply_configuration cleaning/deploy step to interoperate with Redfish
Services that enable a client to indicate when to apply settings via the
Distributed Management Task Force (DMTF) Redfish standard
@Redfish.SettingsApplyTime annotation. [1]

Such services, typically offered by baseboard management controllers
(BMC), may require POST of the annotation, along with the future
intended state of the settings. Otherwise, they may never be applied.
That applies to the Dell EMC integrated Dell Remote Access Controller
(iDRAC).

When the annotation is not supported, it is not POST.

[1] http://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/DSP0266_1.11.0.html#settings-resource

Co-Authored-By: Eric Barrera <eric_barrera@dell.com>

commit_message:
Fix redfish BIOS to use @Redfish.SettingsApplyTime

This change fixes the 'redfish' BIOS interface 'apply_configuration'
cleaning/deploy step to work with Redfish Services that must be supplied
the Distributed Management Task Force (DMTF) Redfish standard
@Redfish.SettingsApplyTime annotation [1] to specify when to apply the
requested settings, such as the Dell EMC integrated Dell Remote Acesss
Controller (iDRAC).

Such services, typically offered by baseboard management controllers
(BMC), require POST of the annotation, along with the future intended
state of the settings. Otherwise, they may never be applied.

When the annotation is not supported, it is not provided with the future

commit_message:
Followup Remove haproxy_check_script for UDP-only

The original patch: Ib2a80afb9223da2c0af6f6add250ffaaa20a316f

First attempt at fixing this issue assumed that the update function
would actually be called again after the initial LB creation, which it
is not. We should ensure that this is called when we do any UDP listener
creation, so the file can be removed if necessary.

Change-Id: Iec1ec7df420e3746b47004c8c0374d2d8274f45b

commit_message:

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch

continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

commit_message:
Use UUID for mounted SwiftRawDisks

When SwiftRawDisks is set, try to mount the disks using uuids instead of
paths. This makes mounts more stable, eg. if a kernel gets updates and
device orders are changed.

This patch will also update existing entries in /etc/fstab and replaces
the device path with the corresponding UUID.

Change-Id: I275b962447015e804638ccf85c63a22d1bb6e3d6
(cherry picked from commit 6206d195928e11de4672404720e137422d619cad)

[{'created': '2020-09-22 17:00:14.000000000', 'message': "[Queens Only] Add rhos-release parameters for UC RHEL/build in FFU

When upgrading the Undercloud in the FFU procedure a sequential
upgrade is carried out. If using rhos-release, the very same
target RHEL version will be configured for the three releases
as the default takes ansible_distribution_version, which as we
come from an OSP10 Undercloud will point to 7.7. Also, the build
will, by default, be 'latest' which can be problematic.

Using the very same RHEL version for the three sequential upgrades
is a problem when getting to the most recent OSP13 build which is
based on RHEL 7.9.

This patch extends the ffu_undercloud_repo_args to include the
appropriate default parameters needed for rhos-release and sets
them for the role execution.

This is queens-only due to this whole mechanism being different in
later branches.

commit_message:
[Queens Only] Add rhos-release build parameter for UC in FFU

When upgrading the Undercloud in the FFU procedure a sequential
upgrade is carried out. If using rhos-release, the 'latest'
build is used by default, which is not what we want.

This patch extends the ffu_undercloud_repo_args to include the
appropriate default parameters needed for rhos-release and sets
them for the role execution.

This is queens-only due to this whole mechanism being different in
later branches.

Change-Id: Ib763e2350724022d71750f53b39d2652c9853a3c

subject: Create stable document ids when pushing logs to elasticsearch
messages: [{'account_id': 16036, 'date': '2020-09-22 11:33:04.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 30491, 'date': '2020-09-23 13:38:00.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1\n\nwe shouldn't be adding this hash key when es is not used"}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-22 11:33:04.000000000', 'message': 'Create stable document ids when pushing logs to elasticsearch

by default fluentd will not generate document _id for every document when
pushing logs to elasticsearch, and elasticsearch will generate a new _id for
each document it receives. In a case of transient failure where elasticsearch
fails to process logs in time (resulting in timeout from fluentd side, or
timeout from proxy in-between) fluentd will retry an entire request as it has
no way of telling what has been processed.
This can lead to fluentd entering a loop where it tries to push the same data
into elasticsearch over and over, finally overloading it completely.

This commit enables filter bundled with fluentd-plugin-elasitcsearch[1] that
generates an unique _id for each and every document before uploading them
into elasticsearch, so that it can be deduplicated by the cluster.

Closes-Bug: #1896610

[1]: https://github.com/uken/fluent-plugin-elasticsearch#generate-hash-id

Change-Id: Ifd0544b0ec982e756d6d859f8f233a65208e7a0c
'}]
commit_message:
Create stable document ids when pushing logs to elasticsearch

by default fluentd will not generate document _id for every document when
pushing logs to elasticsearch, and elasticsearch will generate a new _id for
each document it receives. In a case of transient failure where elasticsearch
fails to process logs in time (resulting in timeout from fluentd side, or
timeout from proxy in-between) fluentd will retry an entire request as it has
no way of telling what has been processed.
This can lead to fluentd entering a loop where it tries to push the same data
into elasticsearch over and over, finally overloading it completely.

This commit enables filter bundled with fluentd-plugin-elasitcsearch[1] that
generates an unique _id for each and every document before uploading them
into elasticsearch, so that it can be deduplicated by the cluster.

Closes-Bug: #1896610

[1]: https://github.com/uken/fluent-plugin-elasticsearch#generate-hash-id

Change-Id: Ifd0544b0ec982e756d6d859f8f233a65208e7a0c

commit_message:
Remove duplicate top call in containers

podman/docker top $container does the same as running 'top'
inside the containers, so let's drop the dup.
Change-Id: I40c5782ab0e690cfde78d06d19d58dbcac480081

[{'created': '2020-09-22 09:30:05.000000000', 'message': 'test_evacuate.sh: Stop using libvirt-bin

I49dc963ada17a595232d3eb329d94632d07b874b missed that
call_hook_if_defined will actually cause the entire run to fail [1] if
we attempt to stop the non-existent libvirt-bin service so just remove
it now we are using the train UCA.

[1] https://opendev.org/openstack/devstack-gate/src/commit/7a70f559c559e22b498d735b4ed20aadc71b7f39/functions.sh#L74

Change-Id: Ife26f1ceb6208e12328ccdccbab0681ee55d5a2a
'}]
commit_message:
test_evacuate.sh: Stop using libvirt-bin

I49dc963ada17a595232d3eb329d94632d07b874b missed that
call_hook_if_defined will actually cause the entire run to fail [1] if
we attempt to stop the non-existent libvirt-bin service so just remove
it now we are using the train UCA.

[1] https://opendev.org/openstack/devstack-gate/src/commit/7a70f559c559e22b498d735b4ed20aadc71b7f39/functions.sh#L74

Change-Id: Ife26f1ceb6208e12328ccdccbab0681ee55d5a2a

[{'created': '2020-09-17 21:18:48.000000000', 'message': 'Fix tempest workspace initialization

Logic for renaming existing workspaces needs to be changed. It
raises an error when it tries to init an existing workspace name.

can run successfully.

Closes-Bug: #1896126
'}]
commit_message:
Fix tempest workspace initialization

Logic for renaming existing workspaces needs to be changed. It
raises an error when it tries to init an existing workspace name.

This change renames all existing workspaces so that workspace init
can run successfully.

Change-Id: I735695cc1107721d48bd0c30eb3a68b762da5b0d
Closes-Bug: #1896126

subject: Get the CIDR of the neutron port for NetworkConfig
messages: [{'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2020-09-22 08:57:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Cherry Picked from branch master.'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2020-09-22 18:11:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2020-09-22 18:11:21.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2020-09-23 06:37:57.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:\n\nrecheck'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-22 08:57:06.000000000', 'message': "Get the CIDR of the neutron port for NetworkConfig

Since GroupVars moved to overcloud.j2.yaml in
https://review.opendev.org/677218 the CIDR set in
'{{network.name_lower}}_cidr' in groupvars is limited
to one of the subnets on the network.

When a network have multiple subnets with different
subnet prefixes, this becomes a problem as nodes are
configured with the from subnet mask.

This change moves them to AnsibleHostVars.

Closes-Bug: #1895899
Change-Id: I4e4e5b1195d17f59c825a3f7df73920921e1f86e
(cherry picked from commit cd53ae79c79650c4ad1e774dad0bce60a3078c69)
"}]
commit_message:
Get the CIDR of the neutron port for NetworkConfig

Since GroupVars moved to overcloud.j2.yaml in
https://review.opendev.org/677218 the CIDR set in
'{{network.name_lower}}_cidr' in groupvars is limited
to one of the subnets on the network.

When a network have multiple subnets with different
subnet prefixes, this becomes a problem as nodes are
configured with the from subnet mask.

This change moves them to AnsibleHostVars.

Closes-Bug: #1895899
Change-Id: I4e4e5b1195d17f59c825a3f7df73920921e1f86e
(cherry picked from commit cd53ae79c79650c4ad1e774dad0bce60a3078c69)

commit_message:
Generate a TLS certificate and send it to ironic

Adds a new flag (on by default) that enables generating a TLS
certificate and sending it to ironic via heartbeat. Whether
ironic supports auto-generated certificates is determined by
checking its API version.

Change-Id: I01f83dd04cfec2adc9e2a6b9c531391773ed36e5

commit_message:
check expired notifications

Occasionally, there would be notifications which will remain 'new',
'error' or 'running' status all times, and not to be processed again.
Due to this, operator can not update the segment or host.

This patch add one task to periodically check unfinished notifications.
If one unfinished notification is expired, just set its status to
'failed'.

Close-Bug: #1773765
Change-Id: If49635639dd976aeec3ea73e702ad2636fcf1e0a

commit_message:
Fix l-c testing for ubuntu focal

As per victoria cycle testing runtime and community goal[1]
we need to migrate upstream CI/CD to Ubuntu Focal(20.04).

- Bump the lower constraints for required deps which added python3.8 support
in their later version.

Story: #2007865
Task: #40206

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/selected/victoria/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal.html

Change-Id: If3ec085184fbba81f455164b803afb6f66e46fd0

commit_message:
Skip allowed_cidrs definition when Octavia provider is ovn

When ovn provider is used Octavia does not support the
allowed_cidrs option defined on the Listeners. This commit
ensures this option is only present when Amphora provider is
used.

Change-Id: I6f4c7d5d75231672748acecc1f65525bb06cb899

commit_message:
Limit inspector jobs to 1 testing VM

Currently ironic-base defaults to 2 and our tests try to introspect
all of them. This puts unnecessary strain on the CI systems, return
the number back to 1.

commit_message:
Fix CA file for nova client

If a custom CA file is configured via nova_ca_certificates_file,
currently communication with Keystone will fail, since the session is
not created using this CA file. The same is true for nova_api_insecure.

This change fixes the issue by using a keystoneauth session loader.

Closes-Bug: #1873736

Change-Id: I54a4f398a06c61e0f6f8f3efd3e4b6214bca756b
(cherry picked from commit 3bd82c776c91bdd1caee474f3fc9cda18927da7f)

commit_message:
Use keystoneauth1 config option loading for masakari client

If a custom CA file is configured via [api] cafile, currently
communication with Keystone will fail, since the session is not created
using this CA file. The [api] insecure option is also ignored.

This change fixes the issue by using keystoneauth loading for the auth
and session, to ensure all standard configuration options are supported.

Change-Id: Idd58b72f7f5242e8135fec71b42adf5dd1852417
Closes-Bug: #1873736
(cherry picked from commit e70404588002222c8475667ff1a94f4c265a8def)

commit_message:
Expose new  parameter `NovaVGPUTypesDeviceAddressesMapping`

To support multiple vgpu types configuration, add new
parameter `NovaVGPUTypesDeviceAddressesMapping` where vgpu-type
is key and list of device_addresses are value.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/750148/
Change-Id: Ifc30bbef66717cafb5ec2262be8fe07af1e60772

subject: Do not use OSC in infra playbook
messages:
[{'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2020-09-07 20:31:24.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2020-09-08 16:37:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

Looks better from filtering and good use of limits.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2020-09-17 14:43:03.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I think we should be using osc for this, and I'm not sure what optimization really matters in this case. It's run once after the tests are done. What's the gain here?"}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2020-09-18 16:03:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> I think we should be using osc for this,

Well that's the part where we disagree. I don't see any reason why we should use osc, we do not support or endorse it for Glance, I see absolutely no reason why it should be used in something interfacing with glance-api and shipped in Glance repo.

 > and I'm not sure what
 > optimization really matters in this case.

Using the filters and limits might make big difference, specially in environments where there is lots of images, on top of not needing to depend and load all the bloat osc brings in.

 > It's run once after the
 > tests are done. What's the gain here?

If the intended usage is just our infra ran tests, why it's not living under the glance/tests/ in the first place? Makes me wonder no less, why we should use osc, we don't support in the first place, for something we're relying our testing on."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2020-09-18 16:52:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

> Using the filters and limits might make big difference, specially
 > in environments where there is lots of images, on top of not
 > needing to depend and load all the bloat osc brings in.

There should be one image visible when this runs, only during a zuul job that actually calls it, of which there is precisely one.

 > If the intended usage is just our infra ran tests, why it's not
 > living under the glance/tests/ in the first place? Makes me wonder
 > no less, why we should use osc, we don't support in the first
 > place, for something we're relying our testing on.

Because this is where playbooks for infra stuff lives? For example:

https://github.com/openstack/nova/tree/master/playbooks

https://github.com/openstack/neutron/tree/master/playbooks

https://github.com/openstack/cinder/tree/master/playbooks"}, {'account_id': 5202, 'date': '2020-09-22 17:09:25.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2020-09-23 01:40:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I still don't think we should merge this, but if we do, I'd like to have my -1 on it :)"}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2020-09-23 03:02:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2020-09-23 05:52:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2020-09-23 06:42:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review+2

As per our documentation we still does not support OSC, even though this is infra related stuff I still think we should use supported python-glanceclient only until OSC supports 100% of glance features.

Thank you!'}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2020-09-23 07:20:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 9303, 'date': '2020-09-23 08:53:20.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Workflow+1

Consistent with glance's core team decision as well as documentation saying not to use OSC until it is fully supported."}]

commit_message:
Add volume local cache support

Try to leverage cache software, such as Open CAS, use high performance
disk (e.g. Intel Optane SSD) or persistent memory as the cache in
compute node locally for low performance volume that allocated by cinder
from remote backend storage.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/663549/
Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/#/c/700799/
Change-Id: I70b82a25b57266ad4285f995c21aebce8a020812
Implements: blueprint support-volume-local-cache
Signed-off-by: Liang Fang <liang.a.fang@intel.com>

The only thing that depends on this secret is OCCM which can consume it via secrets. Thoughts?'}, {'account_id': 6484, 'date': '2020-09-02 08:37:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> Yep, I agree with you that the cloud-config should be stored as
 > secrets. That will be the next step.

we have it already, in OCCM we mount a hostpath on master nodes which as secure as possible. Having a secret which means it is in etcd on the master nodes offers a similar level of security or even less since the etcd server maybe compromised or have a bug and so on.
https://github.com/openstack/magnum/commit/ca442a72021dc331612b40e2395fab6879355cf3

What are the next steps?'}, {'account_id': 6484, 'date': '2020-09-07 10:09:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Remove cloud-config from k8s worker node

Now Magnum is not deploying any service or workload on k8s
worker nodes which need to get credentials from local to talk
to Magnum control plane. So the cloud-config file should be
removed from worker nodes to reduce the attach surface from
a security point of view.

Task: 40791
Story: 2008090

Change-Id: I72e418491cbd19291527bbe4b504d599c740fea9

commit_message:
Limit inspector jobs to 1 testing VM

Currently ironic-base defaults to 2 and our tests try to introspect
all of them. This puts unnecessary strain on the CI systems, return
the number back to 1.

Changed l-c job to use ubuntu-bionic to avoid failures

Change-Id: I178190ee1e9d99e60994a307044105f306d4cab3
(cherry picked from commit 2f6df39e028c173453030d8eb150ac3683c8482a)

commit_message:
Update master for stable/victoria

stable/victoria.

commit_message:
Centralized logging minor fixes

This patch contains following fixes to have rsyslog configured properly:

 - Don't use default startmsg.regex for QDR
 - Fixed log path for pacemaker service

This is an automatically generated patch to ensure unit testing

commit_message:
Correct the docstring for _should_enable_unknown_hosts

We open for unknown hosts if either:
 node_not_found_hook is set OR some node is introspected

This matches the method in iptables driver:
ttps://opendev.org/openstack/ironic-inspector/src/branch/master/ironic_inspector/pxe_filter/iptables.py#L33-L38

Change-Id: I4fa06fb879e5d55a383820a52f4ffc7c4b1134a2

commit_message:
Fix cleaning of web-download image import

If import flow fail before reaching the end it never execute
the _DeleteFromFS task and the node_staging_uri is never cleaned up.

Implement the revert() function of the _WebDownload task to remove the
temporary file.

Change-Id: I6dd6a6e2a95a5bd17a80b6256852bb9fac5fa339
Co-Authored-By: Grégoire Unbekandt <gregoire.unbekandt@gmail.com>
Co-Authored-By: Abhishek Kekane <akekane@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1795950

[{'created': '2020-09-21 16:17:01.000000000', 'message': 'CI: Remove the build check for pre-build ramdisks only

In the devstack plugin, we identify RAX hosts and change the settings
slightly to help ensure CI job passage. This is because the machines are
fully emulated as opposed to paravirtualized which causes a performance
impact with our test VMs that we create. Since we can hit issues
while scheduling on RAX in general, it only makes sense to also
swap the job out for centos based IPA jobs that some how happen on
to a RAX node. Since the CI jobs have largely been "de-typed" name
wise, this should be fine.

Change-Id: I63fc5de05c3975433c12ddd9ba21ebb676de2e6c
'}]
commit_message:
CI: Remove the build check for pre-build ramdisks only

In the devstack plugin, we identify RAX hosts and change the settings
slightly to help ensure CI job passage. This is because the machines are
fully emulated as opposed to paravirtualized which causes a performance
impact with our test VMs that we create. Since we can hit issues
while scheduling on RAX in general, it only makes sense to also
swap the job out for centos based IPA jobs that some how happen on
to a RAX node. Since the CI jobs have largely been "de-typed" name
wise, this should be fine.

Change-Id: I63fc5de05c3975433c12ddd9ba21ebb676de2e6c

commit_message:
Don't log NoSuchMethod for special non-existing methods

Such non-existing methods are used as health probes.
Please see bug for details.

Change-Id: I8f6b4a669ec11721f76cf03abcd7d802c3c11eb5
Closes-Bug: #1857319

commit_message:
Avoid double slash in Keystone auth_url

The auth_url parameter is constructed from several configuration values,
including os_auth_prefix which defaults to an empty string. This can
result in a Keystone auth_url containing a double slash, which appears
to cause issues in some deployments.

Change-Id: I9e78e5ef1c29c88d3dc16447a78a6e53c5a71567
Closes-Bug: #1856658
(cherry picked from commit 3167277843986efe50a03dc15e04acf2ef742fef)

commit_message:
Move "NFV" tab under "Project" instead of top-level

Tacker UI table "NFV" is currently anchored directly at the top-level
alongside Admin, Identity and Developer. To be consistent with other
projects, Tacker's NFV tab is moved under "Project" tab.

Closes-Bug #1589700

Change-Id: I1e87dfed574b14e50b3352938bfeeb87d7eb53f6

commit_message:
Make the standalone-redfish job voting

It was supposed to be made voting shortly after the split, but we
sort of forgot. It provides coverage for things (like ansible deploy)
that we used to have voting jobs for.

Change-Id: Id99586d5e01b940089d55c133d9181db05bfdc7e

commit_message:
Update master for stable/victoria

Add file to the reno documentation build to show release notes for
stable/victoria.

Use pbr instruction to increment the minor version number
automatically so that master versions are higher than the versions on
stable/victoria.

Change-Id: I4ed9e59dc749ca89a84fb730d9eeeb66674f3125
Sem-Ver: feature

Screenshots available in https://imgur.com/gallery/kzjl1Uf. Initial implementation simply adds a new panel with all user messages in a single place. Cinder implementation of user messages adds a tab in the detailed view for each resource (volume, snapshot, etc) and places all user messages for that specific resource, but there is no unified view of messages. IMHO it's easier for an operator to see all messages in a single place, although I see the utility of having them filtered as well. In other words, I think we should have redundancy and have both the panel and the tabs per resources showing user messages. Thanks for answering to my comments, Victoria!
Regarding the coverage for api/manila.py, it's a little weird since all the methods you've inserted are being covered by unit tests, so if we do want to increase the coverage on this file, I think that tests for existent methods should be written.
I have addressed two other suggestions to help increasing coverage for two other files.
For manila-ui, I recall we do have some kind of share replicas control but they are a bit different from the way we have for other resources. I mean, we do not have an item in the left menu with "Share Replicas" in the admin dashboard as we have for "Share Snapshots" and "Share types" for instance.
To access the replicas we need to:
Go to shares -> in the shares list, check the actions column.
So in the actions column, there is a dropdown/button containing the actions we have for that share. In the options there is "Migrate share", "Delete share" and "Manage replicas". So if we click in manage replicas, we are redirected to a panel with share replicas information.
I haven't checked if the "Manage replicas" option is exhibited only when a share can be replicated, since I performed all the tests using backends that support replication and shares that could be replicated.
Also, as far as I understood it is not possible to promote or create share replicas using this view.
Anyways, this would be only a usability improvement that could also be done in a follow up patch in the future and I'm okay with this patch being merged.
Btw, great job on this patch :)'}, {'account_id': 6413, 'date': '2020-09-09 20:24:37.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 6413, 'date': '2020-09-09 20:57:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
Don't use rescue to skip cell actions

We shouldn't use rescue as a path to skip the nova actions in the case
of novaless undercloud because it 1) it prints a misleading giant red
FATAL and 2) would not stop if there are problems with the cell tasks.

Change-Id: I40d7113f2a141f9e672a54850c6cc3d782655af1
(cherry picked from commit b0377e3d15c48369eed5867eec600932d9ddb8b8)

commit_message:
Remove become from rhos-release task

In Ansible 2.8+ the following error occurs when using 'become'
on a task inclusion:

ERROR   <class 'ansible.errors.AnsibleParserError'>: 'become'
is not a valid attribute for a IncludeRole

The rhos-release role already uses become correctly on individual
tasks so this argument isn't required on this task.

Change-Id: I072cfb33ff91cb765f8a241e1f865cd9f3ce5725

commit_message:
Add tag's with network_data info to neutron net

Working on a tool to extract deployed networks from an existing
heat stack, adding this information so that it's available for
export.

Also when (if) we remove OS::Neutron::Net, OS::Neutron::Subnet
resources from THT storing this state in the neutron networks
will make it possible to recreate network_data in case the file
is deleted.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/750662
Change-Id: I696afb8f24cc2fdeb17aaef1d3bc3a5fc22a8dcd

commit_message:
[Glusterfs] Fix delete share, Couldn't find the 'gluster_used_vols'

When we have multiple share driver backends, create a shared instance,
and the list of'self.gluster_used_vols' will only be updated on the
current node. If the RPC request to delete the share instance is sent
to other nodes,'self.gluster_used_vols' will be Cannot find the
information of the glusterfs volume we want to delete, so we need to
update'self.gluster_used_vols' when deleting the instance

Change-Id: I14835f6c54376737b41cbf78c94908ea1befde15
Closes-Bug: #1894362
(cherry picked from commit 41b0b95ef67e6c65df3125f94d2fe56b5a3630c6)
(cherry picked from commit 18623a0eebe223c0208d70310a8d0308460bd355)

commit_message:
Switch to newer openstackdocstheme

openstackdocstheme renames some variables, so follow the renames
before the next release removes them. A couple of variables are also
not needed anymore, remove them.

See also
http://lists.openstack.org/pipermail/openstack-discuss/2020-May/014971.html

commit_message:
Image import "web-download" check downloaded size

If the downloaded data size is different from the expected one, the
task "web-download" in the image import process will now fail.

Change-Id: Ie260486d795a6f4af1632f6f3708abc92fb47a3a
Closes-Bug: #1895663

commit_message:
CI: Lower memory usage of VMs/Increase swap

The IPA images we presently build/use for centos are
now smaller than their peak size a few months ago.

As such, we should be able to reduce that memory footprint
and still execcute all of the necessary tests without any
issues.

Also increases the amount of swap to 8GB as the infra
default is now 1GB.

Change-Id: I5705f1f2504803a049ed88a0d8b1d6d0bbccf9e4

[{'created': '2020-09-17 23:54:48.000000000', 'message': 'Unwind the texlive-full addition

Something is missing to make PDF builds continue working on Ubuntu
Focal. Installing texlive-full is an easy answer but pulls in 3gb of
packages and is causing jobs to sometimes timeout. Re-add just the
focused dependencies needed to keep this working without requiring
the kitchen sink.

Change-Id: Id8f50ccd75bbfe5ac126c61fe8e9223e0b6ae2b7
'}, {'created': '2020-09-22 17:26:49.000000000', 'message': 'Replace texlive-full with cm-super

PDF builds need to continue working on Ubuntu Focal. Installing
texlive-full is an easy answer but pulls in 3GB worth of additional
packages and is causing jobs to frequently hit build timeouts.
Re-add just the focused dependencies needed to keep this working
without requiring the kitchen sink.

commit_message:
Replace texlive-full with cm-super

PDF builds need to continue working on Ubuntu Focal. Installing
texlive-full is an easy answer but pulls in 3GB worth of additional
packages and is causing jobs to frequently hit build timeouts.
Re-add just the focused dependencies needed to keep this working
without requiring the kitchen sink.

This is a partial revert of 3f5d26a1c0d773c05e356775cf9ca6612b1ff905
which initially added texlive-full in an attempt to solve PDF build
issues.

Change-Id: Id8f50ccd75bbfe5ac126c61fe8e9223e0b6ae2b7

commit_message:
Add dashboard_tls_external ceph-ansible parameter

This change adds the dashboard_tls_external parameter
to the ceph-ansible group_vars when tls-everywhere is
enabled.
By doing this ceph-ansible looks for cert/keys on the
overcloud nodes (where certmonger generates them)
instead of assuming they're present in the undercloud.

Change-Id: Ia8f537d847c1854893df0646fb59edfb2536de89
(cherry picked from commit 53d892a73c2265455f785a1b499d7bcaa0702039)

commit_message:
Add no_log to os_user async status

When verbosity is turned up, the result of the os_user async may contain
sensitive information so we should leverage the sensitive log variable
for it.

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-05-08 02:56:28.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: Accommodate GET HTTP 202 status without Location

When a GET request is performed on an asynchronous operation task
monitor URI, the iDRAC service can return the HTTP '202 Accepted' status
code without a 'Location' header. This has been observed when issuing a
request for the long-running OEM Server Configuration Profile (SCP)
import and export system configuration operations. [1] sushy-oem-idrac
has required the 'Location' header to continue to query the status of
the operation, and determine when it has completed and whether it
succeeded.

Instead of failing, this change accommodates a missing 'Location' header
by reusing the URI provided in the 'Location' header of the response to
a previous request.

[1] Pushkala Iyer et al., "Server Cloning with Server Configuration
Profiles", (Dell Inc., version 1.1, July 2016),
https://downloads.dell.com/solutions/dell-management-solution-resources/Server Cloning with Server Configuration Profiles 1_1 Final.pdf.

Story: 2007640
Task: 39697
Change-Id: I07eef4bab7285d2c454a6112a43b0725e8ee5a09

commit_message:
Fix GET HTTP 202 status without Location

When a GET request is performed on an asynchronous operation task
monitor URI, the iDRAC service can correctly return the HTTP '202
Accepted' status code without a 'Location' header. [1] This has been
observed while querying the status of the long-running OEM Server
Configuration Profile (SCP) import and export system configuration
operations. [2]

sushy-oem-idrac has incorrectly required the 'Location' header to
continue to query the status of the operation, and determine when it has
completed and whether it succeeded. This fixes that by reusing the URI
provided in the 'Location' header of the response to a previous request,
instead of failing.

[1] http://redfish.dmtf.org/schemas/DSP0266_1.11.0.html#asynchronous-operations
[2] Pushkala Iyer et al., "Server Cloning with Server Configuration
Profiles", (Dell Inc., version 1.1, July 2016),
https://downloads.dell.com/solutions/dell-management-solution-resources/Server
Cloning with Server Configuration Profiles 1_1 Final.pdf.

Co-Authored-By: Derek Higgins <derekh@redhat.com>
Story: 2007640
Task: 39697
Change-Id: I07eef4bab7285d2c454a6112a43b0725e8ee5a09

commit_message:
DNM - debugging with netconsole

Trying to capture dmesg log at crash time with
netconsole.  Highly speculative, though I can make
netconsole run locally at home with machines on the
same LAN, trigger a crash, and see it on the other
machine.

Change-Id: Ie393a50d377d47ddcdcbe20cd39a535af1b4fe7d

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for zun

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for zun.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: I7532998dd5a68e4fde92b053f85b14b3902e6778
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

"}]
commit_message:
Get the CIDR of the neutron port for NetworkConfig

Since GroupVars moved to overcloud.j2.yaml in
https://review.opendev.org/677218 the CIDR set in
'{{network.name_lower}}_cidr' in groupvars is limited
to one of the subnets on the network.

When a network have multiple subnets with different
subnet prefixes, this becomes a problem as nodes are
configured with the from subnet mask.

This change moves them to AnsibleHostVars.

Closes-Bug: #1895899
Change-Id: I4e4e5b1195d17f59c825a3f7df73920921e1f86e
(cherry picked from commit cd53ae79c79650c4ad1e774dad0bce60a3078c69)

commit_message:
Fixes API list handling of unscoped tokens

The API list methods were not handling unscoped tokens correctly.
If the API is using the admin_or_owner-policy.yaml policy override file,
and a user used an unscoped token, the API will list objects for all
projects. This patch corrects that issue.
If you are using the default policies, the API handles unscoped tokens
correctly.

Change-Id: I88e64fd5e8a4c709f735be85b85139dbb52e4acd

commit_message:
PowerMax Driver - Replica rdfg suspend fix

Add wait for synchronized rdf pair state when
creating a replica that has an rdf enabled source.
Prevent calling suspend when rdf pair may not have
reached synchronized state after volume creation.

Change-Id: I8b391d02adff831b3bb67e181907032804f96e72
Closes-Bug: 1892718

commit_message:
Updating the paramiko version to 2.7.0 or greater

We have recently observed that ssh-keygen by default
create OPENSSH format for keys and paramiko got the
support for decrypting it from paramiko 2.7.0[1]

We have recenlty seen failures in whitebox plugin but
considering this can also be observe in tempest as well
it's good to update the version here too.

[1]: http://www.paramiko.org/changelog.html

Change-Id: I3603bbc9787e99fe864a4ec63d49fea6b90a45a8

commit_message:
Focal-related fixes: libguestfs, mysql 8, requirements

- use the the python3 guestfs bindings, not the old python2
  (not availbale anymore on the newer systems);
- fix the compatibility with mysql 8, which unfortunately
  removes the shortend for user creation + password setting;
- bump the values in lower-requirements.txt (also requirements.txt
  and test-requirements.txt when needed) so they they work with
  python 3.8 (inspired by other similar bumps).

Change-Id: Icaa3c008bbe179098244f7bb9d80790068430fe2

commit_message:
Ensure the ansible log file always has a correct UID

This change will ensure that the owner of the ansible.log file is
always set to the executing user, even when the tripleoclient is
invoked using sudo.

> The chagne will pull the UID and should the log file exist it
  will set the UID to the calling user accordingly. In the event
  of an upgrade, or command rerun, the client will ensure we're
  cleaning updating the file UID without user intevention; this
  makes the change transparent to the user and fixes a potential
  UX problem.

Closes-Bug: #1895318
Change-Id: If620fb3026c7420f37b924aa99d62f29a11730a9
Signed-off-by: Kevin Carter <kecarter@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 7d9e41589a252fa6ef1fb0351fc12a75224e4701)

commit_message:
[Glusterfs] Fix delete share, mount point not disconnected

When we delete the shared instance, in addition to erasing the data
in the share, we should disconnect the client's mount point to
prevent the data from being written in.

Closes-Bug: #1886010
Change-Id: I7a334fb895669cc807a288e6aefe62154a89a7e4
(cherry picked from commit 9d44ba0b6a2d20be6158ff667ff3b81de31f5cad)

commit_message:
Fix backend certificate file paths

In amphora-agent API version 1.0, backend certificate files are uploaded
to /var/lib/octavia/certs/<lb_id>/. However, the "server" line in the
rendered HAProxy configuration sets the certificate paths to
/var/lib/octavia/certs/<listener_id>/ (amphora-agent version 0.5).

This renders an invalid HAProxy configuration file and as result HAProxy
fails to reload with the new configuration, and members marked in ERROR
provisioning status.

Task: 40903
Story: 2008157

Change-Id: I7e2b12f19ee7b172464e809df6342ade1e87fb2e

messages:

I think we should not upload any images with the glance service user (this user should not own anything, expect stuff directly related to the service). I agree that uploading as the admin user might not be idea here, maybe we can change the user to be configurable.'}, {'account_id': 30309, 'date': '2019-05-16 10:15:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1 Workflow-1

> I think we should not upload any images with the glance service
 > user (this user should not own anything, expect stuff directly
 > related to the service). I agree that uploading as the admin user
 > might not be idea here, maybe we can change the user to be
 > configurable.

Now I get the idea behind the admin user choice, sure that seems reasonable. However, using `node['openstack']['image_api']['conf']['keystone_authtoken']` namespace to get:

  - project_name
  - project_domain_name
  - user_domain_name

is misleading, as we are mixing up admin user properties with glance service user properties.

I'll submit a patch with suggestions to tackle this."}, {'account_id': 30309, 'date': '2019-05-16 10:49:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

> > I think we should not upload any images with the glance service
 > > user (this user should not own anything, expect stuff directly
 > > related to the service). I agree that uploading as the admin user
 > > might not be idea here, maybe we can change the user to be
 > > configurable.
 > 
 > Now I get the idea behind the admin user choice, sure that seems
 > reasonable. However, using `node['openstack']['image_api']['conf']['keystone_authtoken']`
 > namespace to get:
 > 
 > - project_name
 > - project_domain_name
 > - user_domain_name
 > 
 > is misleading, as we are mixing up admin user properties with
 > glance service user properties.
 > 
 > I'll submit a patch with suggestions to tackle this.

Btw, I've dug through the cookbooks for the other services and noticed that glance is the only service which in its `keystone_authtoken` configuration section the project_name is `admin`.

Does this make sense? Shouldn't it be `service`?"}, {'account_id': 11915, 'date': '2019-05-16 11:39:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Code-Review

I am not 100% sure why we kept the admin auth here when we changed it in the other cookbooks, but iirc there was some reason and it was not just forgotten. I guess the easiest way to find out is to align it with the other cookbooks and see if everything still works :)'}, {'account_id': 30309, 'date': '2019-05-16 13:01:30.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

> I am not 100% sure why we kept the admin auth here when we changed
 > it in the other cookbooks, but iirc there was some reason and it
 > was not just forgotten. I guess the easiest way to find out is to
 > align it with the other cookbooks and see if everything still works
 > :)

Good point eheh

From what I can see, from one of our Openstack deployments, there is no problem with the glance_api service using `service` as its `project_name`. I just want to be sure that conceptually this makes sense.

If it does, would you rather have me abandon this patch and make a suggestion for the user be configurable in a new one?'}, {'account_id': 11915, 'date': '2019-05-16 13:49:52.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I think having a configurable user for uploading images would be useful. I am not sure thou if we actually want to implement the needed logic in this cookbook or rather have people add the needed resources/logic to their own wrapper cookbooks. I think a good first step for making image upload easier (and configurable), would be to add a lwrp for this task here https://github.com/openstack/cookbook-openstackclient.'}, {'account_id': 21961, 'date': '2020-09-22 17:44:43.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned

No update in 1.5+ years.'}]

commit_message:
Adding pre-commit

Introduced changes:
- pre-commit config and rules.
- Add pre-commit to pep8 gate, Flake8 is covered in the pre-commit hooks.
- Applying fixes for pre-commit compliance in all code.

Also commit hash will be used instead of version tags in pre-commit to
prevend arbitrary code from running in developer's machines.

pre-commit will be used to:
- trailing whitespace;
- Replaces or checks mixed line ending (mixed-line-ending);
- Forbid files which have a UTF-8 byte-order marker
  (check-byte-order-marker);
- Checks that non-binary executables have a proper
  shebang (check-executables-have-shebangs);
- Check for files that contain merge conflict strings
  (check-merge-conflict);
- Check for debugger imports and py37+ breakpoint()
  calls in python source (debug-statements);
- Attempts to load all yaml files to verify syntax (check-yaml);
- Run flake8 checks (flake8) (local)

For further details about tests please refer to:
https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks

Change-Id: Ic88cf026a74e9da4acaf9e00c50fddd2c8a48fbe
Signed-off-by: Moisés Guimarães de Medeiros <moguimar@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Skip KuryrLoadbalancer creation for Headless Service

Headless Service are not wired by Kuryr as it returns
directly the Pod's IPs behind the Service and do not
load-balance between them. This commit makes sure a klb
CR is not created for headless services as a LB won't
get created for it.

Change-Id: Ib389ddd5edca44c713149adc13486ab0b08007d2

commit_message:
Leaks of loadbalancer

In theory with the usage of Finalizers having leaks of loadbalancers
is not possible anymore, and if the CRD is deleted it gets recreated
and also the loadbalancer is recreated.

This commit is deleting ensure_release_lbaas and _cleanup_leftover_lbaas
functions.

Change-Id: I0db62a845b23a32eef4358368332c4da2cad5460

commit_message:
PY3: skip jupyter notebook test

Currently junyter noteboot test is broken because of incompatible
packages installed, and needs some fixes to work with the latest
jupyter/ipython. Let's disable testing to unblock our gate until
we fix these issues.

Change-Id: Id7098603df7d2204b48fdb924f4d7b55db4024c1

commit_message:
Add _max_microversion for aggregates

Since compute api 2.41[1] uuid filed has been added to the
aggregates. We should be able to return it in the aggregate object

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/nova/latest/reference/api-microversion-history.html#id38

Change-Id: If02a711e02fd72989cde8e2c25e5b4569ffe628e

commit_message:
Add additional compute flavor operations

In order to proceed with switching flavor in OSC from novaclient/self
api onto SDK few new methods need to be supported.
Those include flavor access and set of extra_specs related operations.
While extra_specs in terms of SDK should be a separate resource, it is
not easy to implement it this way. On the other hand all those
operations are definive subset of flavor related operations.

In addition also merge FlavorDetail into Flavor class

Change-Id: Ia4f60acce5e0e5665e2ba704fe4cd0ec81437eb5

commit_message:
PowerMax Driver - Migrate extra spec class fix

Add in cast when getting extra specs of new volume
type during migrate operations. CoercedDict forces
all assignments to be string. Change this to standard
Dict to allow for int & dict assignments.

Change-Id: I18361315da9630e735044e1e7fb720c554a80456

[{'created': '2020-09-11 10:26:34.000000000', 'message': 'Add some compute console operations

In order to switch OSC to SDK for managing consoles add few missing
(optimize existing) bits:
- add server.get_console_url (deprecated, but still might functional)
- add tests for server_remote_console
- add compute.create_console, which depending on the supported
  microversion invokes appropriate underlaying operation.
- add some console type validations to fail early

Change-Id: I63e752e70fb394fadf88057d71669514532cdddf
'}]
commit_message:
Add some compute console operations

In order to switch OSC to SDK for managing consoles add few missing
(optimize existing) bits:
- add server.get_console_url (deprecated, but still might functional)
- add tests for server_remote_console
- add compute.create_console, which depending on the supported
  microversion invokes appropriate underlaying operation.
- add some console type validations to fail early

Change-Id: I63e752e70fb394fadf88057d71669514532cdddf

commit_message:
[NetApp] Fix python-manila package version

NetApp ONTAP Manila driver fails to get information from 'python-manila'
package in the periodic tasks, and logs INFO messages saying the package
was not found. It doesn't break anything, but the message might be scary.

Change-Id: I2e773f7cca0c95d18922281832afd93a99de5123
Closes-Bug: #1886232

commit_message:
docs: fix aggregate weight multiplier property names

The documentation states that property names for aggregate weight
multipliers should be prefixed with 'filter_scheduler.', however in
reality they should not.

This change fixes this in the documentation.

Change-Id: I3adabb052a859cccf59655c91cc366fbe1cf8386

commit_message:
Update kernel args grub file entry inline with upgrade changes

For FFU, leapp tool requires the /etc/default/grub file
to have entries to start with "GRUB". upgrade_steps for
ffu has been updated to fix it for FFU. Align the args
with the same name for the fresh deployment too.

Related-Bug: #1890769
Change-Id: I2349f30d2159e068ebdb453372050459b7a78c65
(cherry picked from commit e0ece7e5a3ea3fc3b451963a7bab4ae0ece12600)

commit_message:
doc: correct the link to user/flavor.rst

In commit a76277f81a005cb48088fd9452637b4e7ee1b9f5, the introduction
of flavor extra specs, such as 'hw:cpu_policy', 'hw:cpu_thread_policy'
and ... , have been moved to 'doc/source/user/flavors.rst' from
'doc/source/admin/flavors.rst', while in 'cpu-topologiest.rst' this
change hasn't been updated. Apply this change.

Change-Id: I031a5ea6de00a8c5cf67897ddb78075c8bc79c0b
Signed-off-by: Wang Huaqiang <huaqiang.wang@intel.com>

commit_message:
sphinxext: Add 'merge_domaindata'

This is necessary to enable parallel builds. As noted in the Sphinx docs
[1], this method has the following function:

  Merge in data regarding docnames from a different domaindata inventory
  (coming from a subprocess in parallel builds).

Given how simple the datatypes we're storing are, this is pretty easy to
implement.

[1] https://www.sphinx-doc.org/en/master/extdev/domainapi.html#sphinx.domains.Domain.merge_domaindata

Change-Id: I46c7903b159f99c68896a4c3c4d20daef848f9c2
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <sfinucan@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1895162

commit_message:
Add octavia-grenade to the check queue (non-voting)

The octavia-grenade job has been migrated to a Zuul v3 native job. It
has been working fairly well and is a voting job in Octavia gate.

commit_message:
Avoid double slash in Keystone auth_url

The auth_url parameter is constructed from several configuration values,
including os_auth_prefix which defaults to an empty string. This can
result in a Keystone auth_url containing a double slash, which appears
to cause issues in some deployments.

Change-Id: I9e78e5ef1c29c88d3dc16447a78a6e53c5a71567
Closes-Bug: #1856658

[{'created': '2020-07-21 11:28:24.000000000', 'message': 'Add pre-commit

pre-commit will be used to:
- trailing whitespace [1].
- Replaces or checks mixed line ending (mixed-line-ending) [1].
- Forbid files which have a UTF-8 byte-order
  marker (check-byte-order-marker) [1].
- Checks that non-binary executables have a proper
  shebang (check-executables-have-shebangs) [1].
- Check for files that contain merge conflict
  strings (check-merge-conflict) [1].
- Check for debugger imports and py37+ breakpoint()
  calls in python source (debug-statements) [1].
- Attempts to load all yaml files to verify syntax (check-yaml) [1].
- replace tabs by space (4 by default)(remove-tabs) [2].
- Run flake8 checks (flake8) (local)

[2] https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks
[3] https://github.com/Lucas-C/pre-commit-hooks

Change-Id: I382aa79f7357a86af11783f59e0f1680d5bed8d0
Signed-off-by: Moisés Guimarães de Medeiros <moguimar@redhat.com>
'}, {'created': '2020-09-22 08:37:37.000000000', 'message': "Adding pre-commit

Introduced changes:
- pre-commit config and rules
- Add pre-commit to pep8 gate, Flake8 is covered in the pre-commit hooks.
- Applying fixes for pre-commit compliance in all code.

Also commit hash will be used instead of version tags in pre-commit to
prevend arbitrary code from running in developer's machines.

pre-commit will be used to:
- trailing whitespace;
- Replaces or checks mixed line ending (mixed-line-ending);
- Forbid files which have a UTF-8 byte-order marker (check-byte-order-marker);
- Checks that non-binary executables have a proper
  shebang (check-executables-have-shebangs);
- Check for files that contain merge conflict strings (check-merge-conflict);
- Check for debugger imports and py37+ breakpoint()
  calls in python source (debug-statements);
- Attempts to load all yaml files to verify syntax (check-yaml);
- Run flake8 checks (flake8) (local)

For further details about tests please refer to:
https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks

Change-Id: I382aa79f7357a86af11783f59e0f1680d5bed8d0
Signed-off-by: Moisés Guimarães de Medeiros <moguimar@redhat.com>
"}]

subject: Make profile tasks host aware
messages: [{'account_id': 14985, 'date': '2020-09-21 13:04:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2020-09-21 19:28:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}]
revisions:
[{'created': '2020-09-21 13:04:17.000000000', 'message': "Make profile tasks host aware

When we switched to free, the task timing isn't accurate because it
records time between two tasks. With free, the tasks may be on different
hosts and not even the same task so the timing was the time between some
tasks.  This rewrite adjusts where we start and stop the task timing and
includes a hostname in the calculation. The inclusion of the hostname
allows us to pinpoint if tasks take longer on specific hosts as task ids
are generally (but not always) the same between hosts.

Change-Id: If0194091eb03186203e7724d506fdd36fd82baeb
(cherry picked from commit c6308a1666bf871f1e51703c9040f14d87e6d708)
"}]
commit_message:
Make profile tasks host aware

When we switched to free, the task timing isn't accurate because it
records time between two tasks. With free, the tasks may be on different
hosts and not even the same task so the timing was the time between some
tasks.  This rewrite adjusts where we start and stop the task timing and
includes a hostname in the calculation. The inclusion of the hostname
allows us to pinpoint if tasks take longer on specific hosts as task ids
are generally (but not always) the same between hosts.

Change-Id: If0194091eb03186203e7724d506fdd36fd82baeb
(cherry picked from commit c6308a1666bf871f1e51703c9040f14d87e6d708)

commit_message:
Stop using profile_tasks as a base

The profile_tasks callback has been moved out of the base ansible code
base as part of 2.10. We already override most of the logic so let's
drop this inclusion to make tripleo_profile_tasks compatible with
ansible >2.9.

Change-Id: Iae3cb2b763eac435a2b8546182d1c65e917516e6
(cherry picked from commit 0afddf7b4cdca7e7e60db16a83b9c9e875751533)

stable/victoria branch for blazar-dashboard.

> >  I'm not even sure I like the idea of introducing users and
 > integration partners to this type of interface change.
 > 
 > The whole intent is move away from heat which would surely involve
 > changing/converting the heat network config templates they use.
 > Though with this interface customers would not be forced to change
 > (they can still keep on using heat)

I have heard other's talk about using heat as a library, with an ephemeral heat stack.
We could also take just the code to process a heat template with parameters, conditionals, yaql, the OS::Heat::Value resource only + output. I.e not changing the interface, but the internals.

Since this is'nt dropping support for heat, I don't see any reason blocking it. But I do think changing the user interface is a bigger discussion."}, {'account_id': 3153, 'date': '2020-09-21 17:27:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add support for network config template

This adds support to use jinja template for network config.
Also adds ones to be used with default undercloud and
standalone.

Though the templates of both undercloud and standalone are
almost the same, separate ones are kept as before.

If someone wants to override the whole config as supported
earlier it can be done by choosing a different template.

Change-Id: I16be7ee44af8f52c8ef0705e2ab692148d65bc28

[{'created': '2020-09-18 12:52:20.000000000', 'message': "defaults: use a versioned path for stackviz/tempestconf virtualenv

When upgrading to Ussuri from Train we already had a virtualenv
called 'stackviz'. As a result the upgrade process attempts to
re-use the same virtualenv, which contains a pip executable for
Python 2. When trying to install Python 3 packages this fails.

We worked around this by using the same path versioning mechanism
used for tempest and other components, forcing the creation of a
new virtualenv. This patch applies this approach to the
virtualenvs for stackviz and tempestconf.

Change-Id: Iad382dfeb91d25c325b41d3adc7f703e0e4688a8
"}]
commit_message:
defaults: use a versioned path for stackviz/tempestconf virtualenv

When upgrading to Ussuri from Train we already had a virtualenv
called 'stackviz'. As a result the upgrade process attempts to
re-use the same virtualenv, which contains a pip executable for
Python 2. When trying to install Python 3 packages this fails.

We worked around this by using the same path versioning mechanism
used for tempest and other components, forcing the creation of a
new virtualenv. This patch applies this approach to the
virtualenvs for stackviz and tempestconf.

Change-Id: Iad382dfeb91d25c325b41d3adc7f703e0e4688a8

- pre-commit config and rules
- Add pre-commit to pep8 gate, Flake8 is covered in the pre-commit hooks.
- Applying fixes for pre-commit compliance in all code.

Also commit hash will be used instead of version tags in pre-commit to
prevend arbitrary code from running in developer's machines.

pre-commit will be used to:
- trailing whitespace;
- Replaces or checks mixed line ending (mixed-line-ending);
- Forbid files which have a UTF-8 byte-order marker (check-byte-order-marker);
- Checks that non-binary executables have a proper

- Check for debugger imports and py37+ breakpoint()
  calls in python source (debug-statements);
- Attempts to load all yaml files to verify syntax (check-yaml);
- Run flake8 checks (flake8) (local)

For further details about tests please refer to:
https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks

commit_message:
Proposing victoria RC1 for kuryr-libnetwork

As a courtesy for project teams, on RC1 week the release management
team proposes a RC1 release for all cycle-with-rc deliverables,
based on HEAD. That RC1 will double as the branch point for the
stable/victoria branch for kuryr-libnetwork.

Release liaison or PTL should +1 this proposal if they are happy
with it, amend this proposal (for example with a more recent SHA)
to match their needs, or -1 to block it until release-critical
issues are all fixed.

Change-Id: I5653259563d9ff4b32690e52a5ac5d19803c15ad
Signed-off-by: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>

commit_message:
Fix accepting 'insert_headers' when unsupported

This patch fixes the Octavia listener API from accepting the
'insert_headers' parameter for protocols that do not support header
insertion.

Change-Id: I4ec2299b64b180f8b2d8f0b8485a6be9fe32d2eb
Story: 2007967
Task: 40464
(cherry picked from commit 08fad7496612962418c81c2d981069bde275157b)

commit_message:
Do not retry locking when heartbeating

IPA will retry any heartbeats anyway, by not retrying on the ironic side,
we 1) make heartbeats quicker, 2) avoid several heartbeats queuing up on
a really busy systems with short heartbeating interval.

Change-Id: If030340a780c759f6433d37b6423d17b72e1a548
Story: #2008167
Task: #40918

commit_message:
Fix pep8 testing for ubuntu focal

As per victoria cycle testing runtime and community goal[1]
we need to migrate upstream CI/CD to Ubuntu Focal(20.04).

Fixing:
- bug#1886296
Bump the pyflakes to 2.1.1 as min version to run pep8 jobs
on py3.8 which is default python vesion in ubuntu focal.

Story: #2007865
Task: #40206

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/selected/victoria/migrate-ci-cd-jobs-to-ubuntu-focal.html

Change-Id: I7f6fbfaa1bae66d8cbd449ab268162791ea71de9

commit_message:
Adding pre-commit

Introduced changes:
- pre-commit config and rules
- Add pre-commit to pep8 gate, Flake8 is covered in the pre-commit hooks.
- Applying fixes for pre-commit compliance in all code.

Also commit hash will be used instead of version tags in pre-commit to
prevend arbitrary code from running in developer's machines.

pre-commit will be used to:
- trailing whitespace;
- Replaces or checks mixed line ending (mixed-line-ending);
- Forbid files which have a UTF-8 byte-order marker
  (check-byte-order-marker);
- Checks that non-binary executables have a proper
  shebang (check-executables-have-shebangs);
- Check for files that contain merge conflict strings
  (check-merge-conflict);
- Check for debugger imports and py37+ breakpoint()
  calls in python source (debug-statements);
- Attempts to load all yaml files to verify syntax (check-yaml);
- Run flake8 checks (flake8) (local)

For further details about tests please refer to:
https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks

Change-Id: Ib18f38dbec90c62e870307bf22a8b4f193237bce
Signed-off-by: Moisés Guimarães de Medeiros <moguimar@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Adding pre-commit

Introduced changes:
- pre-commit config and rules
- Add pre-commit to pep8 gate, Flake8 is covered in the pre-commit hooks.
- Applying fixes for pre-commit compliance in all code.

Also commit hash will be used instead of version tags in pre-commit to
prevend arbitrary code from running in developer's machines.

pre-commit will be used to:
- trailing whitespace;
- Replaces or checks mixed line ending (mixed-line-ending);
- Forbid files which have a UTF-8 byte-order marker
  (check-byte-order-marker);
- Checks that non-binary executables have a proper
  shebang (check-executables-have-shebangs);
- Check for files that contain merge conflict strings
  (check-merge-conflict);
- Check for debugger imports and py37+ breakpoint()
  calls in python source (debug-statements);
- Attempts to load all yaml files to verify syntax (check-yaml);
- Run flake8 checks (flake8) (local)

For further details about tests please refer to:
https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks

Change-Id: I593196cf0d099fe1dcc3a6298fd6cc6b7a883ea2
Signed-off-by: Moisés Guimarães de Medeiros <moguimar@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Revert use of _ceilometer_is_first_play_host for post install tasks

run_once can't be replaced with such condition since config files should
be put against all groups, and not only api one.

Change-Id: I5ead13059f0494d53a2d5961b03e8c618b3f5635

commit_message:
Adding pre-commit

Introduced changes:
- pre-commit config and rules.
- Add pre-commit to pep8 gate, Flake8 is covered in the pre-commit hooks.
- Applying fixes for pre-commit compliance in all code.

Also commit hash will be used instead of version tags in pre-commit to
prevend arbitrary code from running in developer's machines.

pre-commit will be used to:
- trailing whitespace;
- Replaces or checks mixed line ending (mixed-line-ending);
- Forbid files which have a UTF-8 byte-order marker
  (check-byte-order-marker);
- Checks that non-binary executables have a proper
  shebang (check-executables-have-shebangs);
- Check for files that contain merge conflict strings
  (check-merge-conflict);
- Check for debugger imports and py37+ breakpoint()
  calls in python source (debug-statements);
- Attempts to load all yaml files to verify syntax (check-yaml);
- Run flake8 checks (flake8) (local)

For further details about tests please refer to:
https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks

Change-Id: I3640bb690c552a428ae0e8250adffbc3a51a310e
Signed-off-by: Moisés Guimarães de Medeiros <moguimar@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Disable Designate service for scenario 03

Due to recent update of bind package in CentOS-8.2 broke the
designate deployment. Until we get a proper fix, designate
service is disabled.

Related-Bug: #1883692

Signed-off-by: Chandan Kumar (raukadah) <chkumar@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Fix tripleo-repos molecule to run on CentOS/RHEL 8

The current molecule configuration for the tripleo-repos role only
works fine on CentOS 7, since it requires several python2 packages.

Removing the dockerfile switches to the embedded support from molecule.

Depends-On: https://review.rdoproject.org/r/27300
Change-Id: Ic2b5e1d9dcf7bef72cca4be64a46c49d5ccc8bfd

commit_message:
Fix l-c and mysql GRANT syntex for Ubuntu Focal

Also fixing user creation with GRANT in MySQL 8.0(Ubuntu Focal)
Ubuntu Focal (20.04) has mysql 8.0 and with mysql 8.0 there
is no implicit user creation with GRANT. We need to
create the user first before using GRANT command.
Change-Id: I4c0469628e82e86b4023a9b011d09f20f9b66aac
(cherry picked from commit 9a89c304797e8d7f2a64a0516d4aeb085abcefe3)

commit_message:
Make test-setup.sh compatible with mysql8

Starting from mysql version 8 it's not possible to create a user
implictly when using GRANT.

This patch makes the behavior compatible with that.

Change-Id: Ia13402213bc82027e3d658918a22003be26576d6
Co-Authored-By: Sean McGinnis <sean.mcginnis@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Bump hacking min version to 3.0.1

hacking 3.0.1 fix the pinning of flake8 to avoid bringing in a new
version with new checks.

bumping the min version for hacking so that any older hacking versions
which auto adopt the new checks are not used.

Change-Id: I3f4fca9a0df2f45241288fd876064433f4e2f737

commit_message:
Make Actions field in Volume resource optional

In the Volume resource implementation, the Actions field was
incorrectly specified as required. It is normal for Redfish services
to not have this field in the Volume resource. This would cause an
error when reading the Volume resource on any such Redfish service.

Updates the Actions field in the Volume resource to be optional.

Change-Id: I1399d2996d8651f6166a4909f6bdf43994ebee23
Story: 2003514
Task: 40783

commit_message:
Lower default verbosity for ansible

Similar to aef369e7b4d38e4ca7eb158d2878e84a4b93e603 however this only
affects the ansible-playbook execution. By default openstack cli sets
verbosity to 1 so we are always running ansible-playbook with a -v. This
can a consequence on the information returned during execution as we may
get extra result data in the output.

Change-Id: I4e1cb6658172a7da5ae5198ba55d47de33282975

revisions:
[{'created': '2020-07-21 11:43:40.000000000', 'message': 'Add pre-commit

pre-commit will be used to:
- trailing whitespace [1].
- Replaces or checks mixed line ending (mixed-line-ending) [1].
- Forbid files which have a UTF-8 byte-order
  marker (check-byte-order-marker) [1].
- Checks that non-binary executables have a proper
  shebang (check-executables-have-shebangs) [1].
- Check for files that contain merge conflict
  strings (check-merge-conflict) [1].
- Check for debugger imports and py37+ breakpoint()
  calls in python source (debug-statements) [1].
- Attempts to load all yaml files to verify syntax (check-yaml) [1].
- replace tabs by space (4 by default)(remove-tabs) [2].
- Run flake8 checks (flake8) (local)

[2] https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks
[3] https://github.com/Lucas-C/pre-commit-hooks

Change-Id: I9b979afcd45e6a51252ccccb686b01beeb9157f8
Signed-off-by: Moisés Guimarães de Medeiros <moguimar@redhat.com>
'}, {'created': '2020-09-15 12:46:34.000000000', 'message': "Adding pre-commit

Introduced changes:
- pre-commit config and rules
- Add pre-commit to pep8 gate, Flake8 is covered in the pre-commit hooks.
- Applying fixes for pre-commit compliance in all code.

Also commit hash will be used instead of version tags in pre-commit to
prevend arbitrary code from running in developer's machines.

pre-commit will be used to:
- trailing whitespace;
- Replaces or checks mixed line ending (mixed-line-ending);
- Forbid files which have a UTF-8 byte-order marker (check-byte-order-marker);
- Checks that non-binary executables have a proper
  shebang (check-executables-have-shebangs);
- Check for files that contain merge conflict strings (check-merge-conflict);
- Check for debugger imports and py37+ breakpoint()
  calls in python source (debug-statements);
- Attempts to load all yaml files to verify syntax (check-yaml);
- Run flake8 checks (flake8) (local)

For further details about tests please refer to:
https://github.com/pre-commit/pre-commit-hooks

Change-Id: I9b979afcd45e6a51252ccccb686b01beeb9157f8
Signed-off-by: Moisés Guimarães de Medeiros <moguimar@redhat.com>
"}]

We shouldn't use rescue as a path to skip the nova actions in the case
of novaless undercloud because it 1) it prints a misleading giant red

Change-Id: I40d7113f2a141f9e672a54850c6cc3d782655af1

commit_message:
Don't use rescue to skip cell actions

We shouldn't use rescue as a path to skip the nova actions in the case
of novaless undercloud because it 1) it prints a misleading giant red
FATAL and 2) would not stop if there are problems with the cell tasks.

Change-Id: I40d7113f2a141f9e672a54850c6cc3d782655af1

commit_message:
Reduce VMs for multinode and standalone jobs

The minimum amount of disk space on CI test nodes
may be approximately 60GB on /opt with now only 1GB
of available swap space by default.

This means we're constrained on the number of VMs and
their disk storage capacity in some cases.

Change-Id: Ia6dac22081c92bbccc803f233dd53740f6b48abb

commit_message:
Fix manila OverQuota issue while managing shares

Fixes the OverQuota issue while managing shares. Now, when a share
manage request is received and there is no available quota to this
resource, manila will allow the quotas to be exceeded and the
administrator will need to adjust it.

Change-Id: If6edfa79965f1a0e6959b436c53a714217d23f7d
Closes-Bug: #1863298

[{'created': '2020-06-02 17:34:54.000000000', 'message': '[NetApp] Fix CIFS promote back issue

This change fixes the NetApp promote back issue when using CIFS
protocol. When promoting a replica, the NetApp ONTAP driver
attempts to create a new CIFS share entity (an access point as
defined in [1]) for the new active replica. This behavior
causes a failure since the storage identifies that a current
backend CIFS share with the same name exists, considering
that the reffered replica was once the active one.

This issue is addressed by removing the related CIFS share
entity when the replica gets promoted.

[1] https://library.netapp.com/ecmdocs/ECMP1401220/html/GUID-1898D717-A510-4B3D-B2E3-CCDDD5BD0089.html

Closes-Bug: #1879368
Change-Id: Id9bdd5df0ff05ea08881dd2c83397f0a367d9945

commit_message:
[NetApp] Fix CIFS promote back issue

This change fixes the NetApp promote back issue when using CIFS
protocol. When promoting a replica, the NetApp ONTAP driver
attempts to create a new CIFS share entity (an access point as
defined in [1]) for the new active replica. This behavior
causes a failure since the storage identifies that a current
backend CIFS share with the same name exists, considering
that the reffered replica was once the active one.

This issue is addressed by removing the related CIFS share
entity when the replica gets promoted.

[1] https://library.netapp.com/ecmdocs/ECMP1401220/html/GUID-1898D717-A510-4B3D-B2E3-CCDDD5BD0089.html

Closes-Bug: #1879368
Change-Id: Id9bdd5df0ff05ea08881dd2c83397f0a367d9945
